===卡迪夫城===
In July 2009, Hudson signed for [[Football_League_Championship|Championship]] side [[Cardiff_City_F.C.|Cardiff City]] for a fee of £1.075m with an extra £250,000 possible if the Bluebirds reach the [[Premier_League|Premier League]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.charlton-athletic.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=34384 |title=Bluebirds swoop for skipper |publisher=Charltonathletic.co.uk |date=2009-07-02 |accessdate=2009-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/footballnation/cardiff-city-fc/2009/07/02/triple-boost-for-cardiff-city-91466-24053427/ |title=Triple boost for Cardiff City |publisher=[[Western_Mail_(Wales)|Western Mail]] |date=2009-07-02 |accessdate=2009-07-02}}</ref> An on-going contract dispute with midfielder [[Joe_Ledley|Joe Ledley]] led manager [[Dave_Jones_(football_manager)|Dave Jones]] to hand the captaincy to Hudson at the start of the season, the third successive club he had been appointed captain of.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/footballnation/cardiff-city-fc/2009/08/07/mark-hudson-named-cardiff-city-captain-91466-24346744/ |title=Mark Hudson handed Cardiff City captaincy |publisher=[[South_Wales_Echo|South Wales Echo]] |date=2009-08-07 |accessdate=2009-08-08}}</ref> Hudson scored an own goal in a 1–1 draw against his former club [[Crystal_Palace_F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on 17 October 2009 before scoring his first goal for the club three weeks later during a 3–2 defeat to [[Swansea_City_A.F.C.|Swansea City]]. He made his 200th league appearance on boxing day against [[Plymouth_Argyle_F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] and added his second goal of the season on 9 January 2010 against [[Blackpool_F.C.|Blackpool]]. However, his season was dealt a blow when he was ruled out for up to two months after being forced to undergo surgery on a split ankle tendon at the end of January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10335~1949485,00.html |title=Huds out for 10–12 weeks |publisher=Cardiff City F.C. |date=2010-01-29 |accessdate=2010-01-31}}</ref> However he did return in time for the play-offs where Cardiff lost 3-2 to [[Blackpool_F.C.|Blackpool]] in the final.

At the start of the 2010-11 season, Hudson lost his captaincy to local boy, [[Craig_Bellamy|Craig Bellamy]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Craig Bellamy to lead Cardiff City on debut |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cardiff_city/8926215.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 August 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-20}}</ref> but however he did keep his place in the team. On 19 March, Hudson suffered a knee injury in a 3-3 draw with [[Millwall_F.C.|Millwall]], three days later it was confirmed Hudson would be out for up to six weeks.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mark Hudson injury blow for Cardiff City |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cardiff_city/9432841.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=22 March 2011 |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref> Despite reports, Hudson would be out for the season, he returned in Cardiff's 1-0 victory over [[Preston_North_End_F.C.|Preston North End]] on 25 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Preston   0 - 1   Cardiff |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13112165.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=25 April 2011 |accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref> He however missed on the following game against [[Middlesbrough_F.C.|Middlesbrough]] which Cardiff lost 3-0 and was chosen to start in the final game of the season against [[Burnley_F.C.|Burnley]] but was taken off with another injury after 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Burnley   1 - 1   Cardiff |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13247282.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=7 May 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref> Again reports of Hudson season being in doubt were proven wrong as he was proven fit for the first leg of Cardiff's second consecutive play-off campaign.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mark Hudson clear for Cardiff City play-off at Reading |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13340777.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=9 May 2011 |accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref> Cardiff drew the first match against [[Reading_F.C.|Reading]], 0-0 at the [[Madjeski_Stadium|Madjeski Stadium]] but failed to beat them at [[Cardiff_City_Stadium|Cardiff City Stadium]], Cardiff lost the semi-finals 3-0.

Under new manager, [[Malky_Mackay|Malky Mackay]], Hudson regained team captaincy for the 2011-12 season and captained the team to a 1-0 win over [[West_Ham_United_F.C.|West Ham United]]. His first goal of the season came in the [[Severnside_derby|Severnside derby]] on 14 August 2011 against [[Bristol_City_F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Cardiff City 3-1 Bristol City |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14435063.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 August 2011 |accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref> Hudson made his 250th league appearance on 27 August against [[Portsmouth_F.C.|Portsmouth]].
